  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Biography of No Geuk-cheong
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: 'No Geuk-cheong—no one knows from whence he came. His official rank reached no higher than scattered official, advancing to the position of Direct Administrator. His household was poor, and he sought to sell his dwelling, though the sale had not yet been completed. It happened that business called him away to a distant province. His wife, meanwhile, sold the house to Hyeon Deok-su, a court official, for twelve pounds of silver. When Geuk-cheong returned to the capital and learned how much silver had been received, he took three pounds and went to Deok-su, saying: "When I originally purchased this house, I paid only nine pounds. After living there these many years without making any repairs, to receive three pounds more would be improper. I must return it." Deok-su, being himself a man of righteousness, refused to accept it, saying: "Why do you alone uphold what is right, while I do not? How can you expect me to accept?" He would not take the silver. Geuk-cheong replied: "Throughout my life, I have never acted against righteousness. How could I sell dear what I bought cheap, and thus sully myself with greed? If you will not heed me, then I shall return the entire sum and ask that you return my house to me." Forced by his resolve, Deok-su accepted the three pounds. But then he sighed and said: "How could I be anything less than Geuk-cheong? What use would I be then?" And so he took the silver and donated it to a temple. All who heard of this marveled, saying: "In this degenerate age when all chase profit and advantage, can such a man truly exist?" I myself regret that the chronicler did not record the full details of Geuk-cheong''s lineage and other virtuous deeds.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The positions mentioned (散官, 直長同正) were honorary titles in the Korean administrative system
  - key: ''
    value: The donation of silver to a Buddhist temple reflects the spiritual resolution of a moral conflict through religious devotion
